<subSubSection id="C35A6505FF882303FF60FAB6B2F3FA2E" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BFF368EFF882303FF60FAB6B2F3FA2E" blockId="40.[151,1436,1207,1519]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis id="B934EA9CFF882303FF60FAB6B26DFAAE" bold="true" box="[199,309,1367,1391]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
The original description of 
<taxonomicName id="4C404D0DFF882303FDFBFAB9B192FAAE" box="[604,714,1368,1391]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Maiestas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pulviscula">
<emphasis id="B934EA9CFF882303FDFBFAB9B192FAAE" box="[604,714,1368,1391]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">pulviscula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
indicates darker markings than are present on the specimen labelled as 
<typeStatus id="54FB882CFF882303FF42FA99B24BFA4E" box="[229,275,1400,1423]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">type</typeStatus>
(BMNH), except the apical dark patch on the hind tibia is clear. The forewings have extra cross veins that would key out the species in the first couplet of Dash &amp; Viraktamath’s (1998) key. Distant (1908) indicated only 
<specimenCount id="9D46FD07FF882303FAD2FA79B274FA0E" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" type="generic">one specimen</specimenCount>
had been sent by Lefroy but another similar female specimen (topotypic) with the same labels (see above) is also in the BMNH.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
